"It Has Made Me Think": Engaging the Public with the History of Health in the 
Modern Irish Prison.

Cox C(1), Wall O(2).

Author information:
(1)School of History, University College Dublin, Dublin, Republic of Ireland. 
Catherine.cox@ucd.ie.
(2)Radical Humanities Laboratory, University College Cork, Cork, Republic of 
Ireland.

Since the establishment of the modern prison system in the early nineteenth 
century, prisons and prisoners have been construed as sites of moral, social, 
and biological contagion. Historic and contemporary studies show that most 
prisoners experience severe health inequalities, higher rates of addiction and 
mental health issues, and lower life expectancy than the rest of the population. 
They also come from deprived social strata. Yet, these aspects of Irish penal 
history have been largely neglected in academia and popular histories. Our 
article discusses two public history projects-an art installation, The Trial, 
and a museum exhibition, Living Inside-that engaged different publics with the 
long history of health and welfare in Irish prisons. Developed by the research 
team on the Wellcome Trust Investigator Award "Prisoners, Medical Care and 
Entitlement to Health in England and Ireland, 1850-2000," based at University 
College Dublin, the projects adopted different methodologies to engage their 
audiences and explore the experience and management of health and welfare in 
nineteenth- and twentieth-century Irish prisons. We further examine the 
different methodological approaches of each project, their varied aims and 
audiences, and the impacts reported by audiences and participants. The article 
also considers some of the challenges of doing this kind of public history, both 
in terms of working with marginalized communities and presenting research about 
difficult subjects to various audiences.

